\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There is a nice parametrization of the unit circle which we now describe:
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a line which passes through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is not the tangent line to the unit circle at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,0)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathbf{V}(y-m(x+1))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the slope of the line, and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 passes through a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\neq(-1,0)$
\end_inset

 on the unit circle.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 lies on the line 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and the unit circle, we get the relations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{2}+y^{2}-1 & =0,\\
y-m(x+1) & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the second relation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y=m(x+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $m(x+1)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the first relation, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m^{2}=\frac{(1-x)^{2}}{(1+x)^{2}}=\frac{1-x}{1+x}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, to get the following parametrization:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x & =\frac{1-m^{2}}{1+m^{2}},\\
y & =\frac{2m}{1+m^{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

